    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-10-28T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-10-28T19:00:00-05:00" n="341"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d341">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72119/8981</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Special Representative</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HEM1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">House</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-10-29T00:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 29, 1918, midnight</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received October 29, 8.17
                        p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>7. <persName>Cobb</persName> has reported to me the following: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>General opinion of all American correspondents in Paris is that the one
                            definite policy of the Allies at this time is to take the control of the
                            peace negotiations out of the [hands] of President <persName
                                corresp="#p_WW1">Wilson</persName>. The same opinion is expressed by
                            correspondents who have just returned to Paris from London. That also is
                            the tone of a large section of the French papers.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HEM1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Edward House</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
